  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the expectations of parents from their children?",
  "response": "Parental expectations for their children can vary widely depending on cultural, social, and personal factors. However, some common expectations include:\n\n1. **Academic Success:** Many parents expect their children to perform well in school, achieve high grades, and pursue higher education.\n\n2. **Good Behavior:** Parents often look for their children to exhibit positive behavior, including respectfulness, politeness, and obedience.\n\n3. **Responsibility:** Developing a sense of responsibility, including completing chores, adhering to commitments, and taking accountability for their actions.\n\n4. **Respect for Others:** Parents typically expect their children to show respect towards family members, friends, educators, and other individuals.\n\n5. **Honesty:** Being truthful and transparent is often a key expectation.\n\n6. **Independence:** Parents often hope their children will become self-sufficient and capable of handling their personal and professional lives independently.\n\n7. **Emotional Well-being:** Overall mental health and the ability to manage emotions are important expectations. Parents may wish for their children to be resilient and have a positive self-esteem.\n\n8. **Social Skills:** Good communication, interpersonal skills and the ability to build healthy relationships are often desired.\n\n9. **Success in Extracurricular Activities:** Participation and achievement in sports, arts, or other hobbies can also be expected.\n\n10. **Good Work Ethic:** Parents may expect their children to be industrious, motivated, and dedicated to their tasks and future career.\n\n11. **Health and Safety:** Maintaining physical health and practicing safety in daily activities is another common expectation.\n\nIt\u2019s important to note that these expectations should be balanced with understanding, empathy, and flexibility to accommodate the individual needs and aspirations of each child. Unrealistic or high-pressure expectations can sometimes lead to stress or anxiety, so fostering open communication is crucial.",
